    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1874-04-24T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1874-04-24T00:00:00-05:00" n="230" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d230">
                <head>No. 228.<lb/>
                    <hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Washburne</persName> to Mr. <persName type="to">Fish</persName>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Legation of
                                    the United States</hi>,<lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Paris</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1874-04-24">
                            <hi rend="italic">April</hi> 24, 1874</date>.
                            (Received May 7.)</dateline>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 957.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: The news of the President’s veto of the
                        currency bill reached me before noon yesterday by a private dispatch from
                        the office of the New York Herald in London. Very soon after this
                        intelligence was received by the bankers and the public down town through
                        the Havas telegraph agency. It created the greatest excitement among our
                        countrymen and in French financial circles. Everywhere there was one
                        universal shout of approval, and the praise of the President was on all
                        lips, without distinction of politics, “race, color, or previous condition
                        of servitude.” All commended the firmness and patriotism and far-sighted
                        statesmanship of the President. The veto will do an immense good over all
                        Europe.</p>
                <p rend="center">* * * * * * *</p>
                <p>I am, &amp;c.,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>E. B. WASHBURNE.</signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
